23. praeterea: another Lucretian formula of transition. He passes, with an apology for his satirical tone, to the second proof of the unreality of the wish for change, namely, that though men of all trades profess to toil for the sake of attaining the power to rest, they are never satisfied to take the rest.

perfidus caupo. Cp. Sat. 1. 5. 4 ‘ cauponibus malignis.' The purpose of the epithet adds to its sting. He is naming in the ease of each profession what costs the most toil.
